 Breconshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of Coedan, Llanfechell, Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","{Llywrch ap Brn}, Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1270–":"about 1270–Deceased","1268–Male":"1268–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1274–Female":"1274–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1238–Male":"1238–Deceased","1242–Female":"1242–Deceased","1238":"1238","ABT    1300":"about 1300","Abt 1300":"about 1300","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1242":"1242","1274":"1274","Abt 1270":"about 1270","1270":"1270","Of Menai Cmt, Anglesey, Wales":"Menai Bridge, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","of Trecastell,Llywel,Breconshire,Wales":"Llywel, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Of Coedan, Llanfechell, Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","{Llywrch ap Brn}, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: traditional spelling of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"Tudur","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from the Old Celtic form <i>Teutorix</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people, tribe’ and ‘ruler, king’. It has been described as a Welsh form of <i>Theodore</i>, but there is no connection between them, though it is ultimately akin to the Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  <b>Terry</b>   )."],"variants":[{"name":"Tudor","meanings":["Traditional: from the Old Celtic form <i>Teutorix</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people, tribe’ and ‘ruler, king’. It has been described as a Welsh form of <i>Theodore</i>, but there is no connection between them, though it is ultimately akin to the Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  <b>Terry</b>   )."]},{"name":"Tudyr","meanings":["Traditional: from the Old Celtic form <i>Teutorix</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people, tribe’ and ‘ruler, king’. It has been described as a Welsh form of <i>Theodore</i>, but there is no connection between them, though it is ultimately akin to the Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  <b>Terry</b>   )."]}]},{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Tudur Ap Gruffudd was born about 1270, in Menai Bridge, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Gruffudd Ap Maredudd, was 33 and his mother, Mrs. Gruffudd ap Maredudd, was 30. He married Mrs. Tudur ap Gruffudd in 1299, in Church of St Mechell, Anglesey, Wales. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","1238":"1238","ABT    1300":"umbes 1300","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1242":"1242","1274":"1274","Abt 1270":"umbes 1270","1270":"1270","Of Menai Cmt, Anglesey, Wales":"Menai Bridge, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","of Trecastell,Llywel,Breconshire,Wales":"Llywel, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Of Coedan, Llanfechell, Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","{Llywrch ap Brn}, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1274–Female":"1274–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1238–Male":"1238–Kuollut","1242–Female":"1242–Kuollut","1238":"1238","ABT    1300":"noin 1300","Abt 1300":"noin 1300","1268":"1268","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1242":"1242","1274":"1274","Abt 1270":"noin 1270","1270":"1270","Of Menai Cmt, Anglesey, Wales":"Menai Bridge, Anglesey,